Interviews, Observations, and Program Documents: The transcripts, notes, and documents from these sources will be coded for emergent patterns and themes in an exploratory fashion. Measures are not pre-specified. The major topics areas are how CWCC grantees:
     - Interpret the grant's funding opportunity announcement (FOA) and match allowed 
       activities to local community needs; 
     - Develop and maintain partnerships;
     - Collaboratively structure their continuum of services, service intake, and service delivery;
     - Integrate services and align strategies to prevent child maltreatment across partners;
     - Approach staffing and leadership roles;
     - Recruit and assess families to identify and serve with prevention services; and
     - Use data to guide and assess their work.

Collaboration Survey: The Collaboration Survey instrument relies on a well-tested, standardized measure of seven collaboration factors, the Collaboration Assessment Tool (CAT; Marek, Brock &amp; Savla, 2015). The seven factors are: context, members, process, communication, function, resources, and leadership. In addition, the survey will measure respondents' perceptions of current success, perceptions of future success, and background characteristics.

